- Sat 5 Jan 2019. Epidemiological situation report, DRC Ministry of Health
[in French, machine trans., abridged, edited]
https://us13.campaign-archive.com/?u=89e5755d2cca4840b1af93176&id=5452b8674b

The epidemiological situation of the Ebola virus disease in the provinces of North Kivu and Ituri dated 4 Jan 2019:
- Since the beginning of the epidemic, the cumulative number of cases is 614, of which 566 are confirmed and 48 are probable. In total, there were 374 deaths (326 confirmed and 48 probable) and 214 people recovered.
- 127 suspected cases under investigation.
- 1 new case confirmed in Katwa.
- 3 new confirmed case deaths, including 2 in Butembo and 1 in Beni.
- 2 new recoveries released from Butembo ETC.
*Reclassification of cases and deaths by health zone after update of the database.

News of the response
Medical care
------------
- A new 16-bed Ebola treatment center (ETC) opened in Katwa health zone [North Kivu] on 3 Jan 2019. The Beni transit center is operational again after material damage has been repaired. Replacement of stolen equipment during the events of 27 Dec 2018.

Vaccination
-----------
Since vaccination began on 8 Aug 2018, 55 676 people have been vaccinated [total numbers of people vaccinated in North Kivu, Ituri, and Tshopo provinces can be seen at the source URL above].

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Mary Marshall

[The progression of the Ebola outbreak can be followed in the 4 daily reports from the MoH above. The number of cases increases on a daily basis as do deaths, the latter mostly taking places in community centers without proper protection for healthcare workers and family of patients, and not Ebola treatment centers, although deaths in the latter are occurring as well. The new Ebola treatment center (ETC) that opened in Katwa health zone will be helpful in providing an increase in beds in safely operated facilities, and the 2nd repair of the Beni treatment center after damage was inflicted during election unrest is encouraging. But the outbreak appears to continue to simmer. - Mod.LK]

******
[2] Summary
Date: Mon 7 Jan 2019
Source: CIDRAP (Center for Infectious Disease Research and Policy) [abridged, edited]
http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2019/01/ebola-outbreak-continues-grow-multiple-drc-sites


Ebola outbreak continues to grow in multiple DRC sites
------------------------------------------------------
Over the weekend [5-6 Jan 2019] and through today 7 Jan 2019, the ministry of health of the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) recorded 16 new Ebola cases from towns and cities across North Kivu and Ituri provinces, including Butembo (6 cases), Katwa (5), Oicha (2), and 1 each in Mabalako, Kyondo, and Kalunguta.

The outbreak now stands at 625 cases, of which 577 are confirmed and 48 are probable. A total of 377 deaths have been recorded, and 101 suspected cases are still under investigation [see [1] above for numbers as of 8 Jan 2019].

Treatment centers open
----------------------
On 3 Jan 2019, DRC officials opened a 16-bed Ebola treatment center in Katwa health zone to treat more patients in that region, and the ministry of health said the Beni transit center is operational again after the building was attacked during election protests on 27 Dec.

Vaccination efforts are still under way throughout the region, with 56 509 people vaccinated, including 19 619 in Beni, 11 526 in Katwa, 6369 in Butembo, 5550 in Mabalako, health ministry said [see [1] above for numbers as of 8 Jan 2019].

Election results still unknown
------------------------------
SHEA [Society for Healthcare Epidemiology of America], which in a statement called for a coordinated response to the outbreak, said there is no health risk to the US public.

[Byline: Stephanie Soucheray]

--
Communicated by:
